source_code.code:
public class ToDoImpl {
       public void doToDo() {
          System.out.println("Doing something");
       }
    }

public class ToDoDebug1 extends ToDoImpl {
       public void doToDo() {
          super.doToDo();

          System.err.println("Debug info here");
       }
    }

public class ToDoFacade extends ToDoDebug1 {
       // other methods, doToDo() is inherited from base classes
    }

public class ReallyDo {
       public void callingDoToDo() {
          ToDoFacade myToDo = new ToDoFacade();
          myToDo.doToDo();
       }
    }

Bug.WithStack:
We have the following problem:
We have the following class hierarchy: public class ToDoImpl { public void doToDo() { System.out.println("Doing something"); } }
public class ToDoDebug1 extends ToDoImpl { public void doToDo() { super.doToDo();
System.err.println("Debug info here"); } }
public class ToDoFacade extends ToDoDebug1 { // other methods, doToDo() is inherited from base classes }
These classes are part of a library, which is build independently from the projects using it. A dependent program is required to use only the ToDoFacade class. The ToDoDebug1 class is for internal debugging purpuses and never used externally (it is public, because we have to used the ToDoImpl class which is delivered with a public API by another Library).
When I implement the following class:
public class ReallyDo { public void callingDoToDo() { ToDoFacade myToDo = new ToDoFacade(); myToDo.doToDo(); } }
The Sun javac Compiler will generate the following virtual call inside the callingDoToDo method: invokevirtual ToDoFacade.doToDo()
The Eclipse compiler will optimize that call and generate: invokevirtual ToDoDebug1.doToDo() [because it is inherited and not overwritten ?]
Both work normally.But when we remove the ToDoDebug1 class in the hierarchy (which does not remove any method or interface) or exchange it witch a new ToDoDebug2 class (which also does not change the Method API), the eclipse compiled class ReallyToDo is not any longer binary compatible with the changed library and has to be re-compiled with the new library to work, whereas the Sun-javac compiled code is compatible and works flawlessly (the ToDoDebug1 class is _not_ imported or mentioned in the ReallyDo source. The reference is compiled into the class file by the eclipse compiler).
So if one build a Library for customers who only use the ToDoFacade API it is not possible to use different Debug-Between classes or to remove them after a while (the API itself is not changed !). I don't know if this special case is really defined in java's guidelines for binary compatibility, (one can interpret it so or so), but I found a place where it says that the compiler has to invoke the virtual Method of the declared class, and not the super classes method, unless super is explicitly given in the source code.
First question: is there a compiler flag to prevent this behaviour and make it compatible to javac ?
Next question: is this a bug or a feature ? It reduces felxibility somewhat, because sometimes it is necessary (here for debugging purpuses) to insert a public class (because the base class is already public) into a hierarchy without changing the Method/Interface/Field API. Javac is flexible enough, and nothing is broken. Under Eclipse all depending projects have to be rebuild ... (and they do not mention the ToDoDebug1 class in their source, this information is only in the compiled class file). Could you please provide the version of javac used in your example and the compiler options used in Eclipse? Thanks. You got me .. my eclipse settings were 1.3 compliance and i comared that to class files generated with a 1.4.2 javac ... when I set eclipse to 1.4 compliance it did it like 1.4 javac (and the other direction: the 1.3 javac generated the same code as eclipse did when in 1.3 compliance) ... so this was my fault, i close the (not existing) bug Hmmm .. just to mention it: when I use the JDK 1.4.2 javac with -target 1.3 it generates the same virtual call as when using it without -target (which is not calling the base class but the right class), so this seems to be a javac issue and not a JDK compliance issue ... the question is then, whether eclipse should generate class files like javac 1.3 did, or generate class files as javac 1.4 does when it is used with -target 1.3 ... uhoh ... It seems, that this has been discussed in Bug 34000 ... so this is a duplicate

